						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/Dossiers/S-T-Policy/ICKM-MIS-ICT/Related-developments/Bridging-the-data-gap-engaging-developing-country-farmers-in-greenhouse-gas-accounting" title="Bridging the data gap: engaging developing country farmers in greenhouse gas accounting " alt="link">Bridging the data gap: engaging developing country farmers in greenhouse gas accounting </a></h2>

	
					<p>Data on agricultural GHG emissions (fertiliser applications, manure management) can only be obtained by asking the farmers themselves. While the use of mobile device technology for ‘crowd-sourcing’ of land management data is one of the best avenues, challenges still persist such as incentivising farmers to supply information, ensuring timely and accurate reporting, making applications simple and locally relevant. Additionally, improvements are also needed in emission factors/models, better geospatial databases for soils and climate, and deployment of distributed monitoring networks.(<a href="http://iopscience.iop.org/1748-9326/8/2/021001?utm_source=K4DNewsletterEN&amp;utm_medium=Link&amp;utm_campaign=K4D_EN_April2013" target="_blank"><i>Environmental Research Letters</i></a>, Vol. 8 No. 2, 2013)</p>
							<p><span class="date">22/05/2013</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/Dossiers/S-T-Policy/ICKM-MIS-ICT/Related-developments/Bridging-the-data-gap-engaging-developing-country-farmers-in-greenhouse-gas-accounting">Read more...</a>
